# Copy to `.env` and fill in. `.env` is git-ignored; this example file is committed and must never
# carry a real credential.
#
# Env holds ONLY connection strings and the deploy target (Conventions / AD-19). The outlier
# threshold is persisted data (single-row `settings` table), never an env var.

# ─── Database (PostgreSQL 18, pinned across all environments) ──────────────────
# Read by prisma.config.ts, which is the single source of the URL for every Prisma CLI command
# (`migrate dev`, `migrate deploy`, `generate`, `validate`) and for the runtime client.
#
# Local development / integration tests — a disposable Postgres 18. See README § Database.
#   docker run -d --name payroll-pg18 -e POSTGRES_PASSWORD=postgres -e POSTGRES_DB=payroll \
#     -p 55432:5432 postgres:18
#
# This URL connects as the OWNER role (`postgres`), which migrations require: `prisma migrate dev`
# needs CREATEDB for its shadow database. The restricted runtime role (`payroll_app`) is a second,
# non-owning role — see DATABASE_URL_APP below.
DATABASE_URL="postgresql://postgres:postgres@localhost:55432/payroll?schema=public"

# The restricted runtime application role — holds SELECT/INSERT on salary_record but NOT
# UPDATE/DELETE (append-only, Law 5 / AD-18). The application connects as THIS role at runtime;
# only migrations use the owner URL above. Provisioned by prisma/sql/bootstrap-roles.sql.
DATABASE_URL_APP="postgresql://payroll_app:payroll_app@localhost:55432/payroll?schema=public"

# ─── Deployed environments (Neon) — SHAPES ONLY ────────────────────────────────
# Story 1-7. Do NOT uncomment these locally: local development and the integration suite point at
# the Docker Postgres 18 above, on port 55432. Real values live in Vercel environment variables
# (Production) and GitHub secrets (preview pipeline) — never in this file and never in the repo.
#
# The two URLs differ in BOTH role and endpoint, and both differences are load-bearing:
#
#   DATABASE_URL      owner  + DIRECT endpoint  → prisma.config.ts → `migrate deploy` at build
#   DATABASE_URL_APP  app    + POOLED endpoint  → src/adapters/db/client.ts at runtime
#
# The direct endpoint for migrations is a correctness constraint, not a preference. Neon's pooler
# runs PgBouncer in TRANSACTION mode, which hands a connection to another client between statements
# and so discards session state — including session-level advisory locks, the exact mechanism a
# migration runner uses to serialize itself against a concurrent migrator.
#
# Runtime wants the opposite: PgBouncer absorbs far more client connections than Postgres will, and
# is the real answer to "every serverless instance opens its own pool" (see APP_POOL_MAX).
#
# The ONLY textual difference between the two hosts is the `-pooler` suffix on the endpoint id.
# sslmode=require is mandatory — Neon rejects non-TLS connections outright.
#
# DATABASE_URL="postgresql://<owner-role>:<password>@ep-<endpoint-id>.<region>.aws.neon.tech/neondb?sslmode=require"
# DATABASE_URL_APP="postgresql://payroll_app:<password>@ep-<endpoint-id>-pooler.<region>.aws.neon.tech/neondb?sslmode=require"
